column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE HCD PICK-OFF ON THE PD-4. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE TURNED OFF   SECURED THE BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 4 MINUTES A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED DONNING THE PROPER PPE AND WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 6 POLY 2-LITER DISPENSER/CONTAINERS WAS SLIGHTLY AJAR, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS/IN BURSTING TEST.

column168: FRA HM Inspector Steven Myers found HM tank car PROX 47160 placarded class3, UN 3295, loaded with UN3295 Hydrocarbons, Liquid, N.O.S. class 3, PG 1, (natural gasoline) to be venting at the vacuum relief device.  This was reported to BPRR management and SPSI was dispatched by Buffalo & Pittsburgh Railroad (Rita Mager) to investigate and make certified permanent repairs.  Shipper MarkWest Energy, Shawn Dunkle notified.  Upon inspection, SPSI determined defective vacuum relief device and they did not have part, so made temporary repairs (gasket) to eliminate any venting possibility.  Shipper notified car owner, Gunvor, who hired Rescar to make repairs.

column168: On January 10, 2024, one (1) 330-gallo drum of UN2055 had a bad weld and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Mid South Environmental Services (MSES) to remediate the impacted site.  MSES personnel utilized absorbents to remediate the styrene monomer-impacted roadway. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for terminal disposal. On January 12, 2024, MSES personnel arrived back onsite to complete the transfer of product into a new 350-gallon steel tote. Once that has been completed, crews secured the scene and demobilized.

column168: On January 5, 2024, two (2) 55-gallon drums containing UN1206 were punctured by a forklift and released approximately twenty-five (25) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from SET Environmental (SET) to remediate the impacted site. SET personnel placed each damaged 55-gallon drum into two (2) 85-gallon salvage drums. R+L terminal personnel had contained the release with granular absorbents, so crews swept them in with hand tools. SET personnel utilized simple green and absorbent pads to wipe down the impacted trailer. All spent absorbents and any cleanup debris were collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums.

column168: This was the last pick up for the day and when the driver was doing his pick up the customer added more paint waste to the drum and he loaded it on his truck. The drive was about an hour back to the facility to unload for the end of the day. He arrive at approximately 1730 and when he opened the door to unload they noticed the drum was swelling up. The team at the facility emidiatly called for a team to come out and and address the container. The drum expanded to the point of failure at about 1830 before the team could arrive to address the situation. The bottom of the container failed and the contents was released into the truck with around 10 gallons making it to the pavement. They were able to contained it with absorbents and booms from spreading. The team arrived around 1930 to perform the clean up. They dawned the proper PPE and proceeded to clean up the material and overpacking the container to be shipped and disposed of properly. The crew was able to complete this around 2200.
column169: We believe that the paint waste that was added by the customer just before the driver picked up drum may have had an incompatible material in it which caused the reaction. The facility management team is working with the customer to figure out what was the added.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: SequenceEvent: The box was found in the Damages Area wet and torn open.  It did not have any hazardous markings, so I thought it was water/rain from that day.  However, I felt a burning sensation on my wrists and discovered the liquid was battery acid.  It was an undeclared HazMat and a SDS was found to confirm its hazardous status. DescribePack: The FedEx Office box was torn open and soiled.  There were plastic bags of plastic Christmas ornaments spilling out (inner packing).  There were also three Non-HazMat items inside, but they got battery acid on them.  The battery was inside a plastic shopping bag. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: I found a SDS for the battery despite being sent Standard Domestic Residential and lacking any hazardous indications on the box.  I isolated the package and processed it after knowing it was hazardous.

column168: RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO DAMAGED PACKAGE ON THE FLOOR ON PD-3 SECTION DURING THE TWILIGHT SORT. PACKAGE AND CONTENTS WERE A HAZMAT FLAMABLE LIQUID DAMAGE. PACKAGE WAS DAMP BUT NO LIQUID LEAKING FROM PACKAGE. RESPONDER FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET CLEAN UP PROCEDURES AND PLACED PACKAGE AND CONTENTS IN DMP TRAY. PACKAGE WAS TAKEN TO DMN PROCESSING AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.
